5000|$|During World War I, the Cunningham's <b>holiday</b> <b>camp</b> {{had found}} {{use as an}} Internment Camp. With {{the arrival of the}} Second World War, the British Government {{realised}} they could save money by requisitioning the many <b>Holiday</b> <b>Camps</b> around the country rather than building purpose-built camps, for training, stationing troops, internment, and for housing refugees and workers. After the war, most <b>holiday</b> <b>camps</b> in Britain had been damaged by troop occupation; the situation was so bad that questions were raised in parliament.|$|R
